WEBVTT

00:03.530 --> 00:06.241
Both victims work
for ZBZ Security.

00:06.592 --> 00:08.013
Company has a contract

00:08.016 --> 00:12.019
with the Turtle Bay Historical
Society right next door.

00:12.021 --> 00:14.238
Now, nothing's missing
from the museum.

00:14.240 --> 00:15.656
We're canvassing
the area

00:15.658 --> 00:18.525
for the gun, shooter,
any possible witnesses.

00:18.527 --> 00:21.078
So, thoughts?

00:22.313 --> 00:24.615
Holmes?
Thoughts?

00:24.617 --> 00:25.616
Sorry, sorry.

00:25.618 --> 00:27.651
I was waiting
for Miss Watson.

00:27.653 --> 00:29.620
I'm training her to analyze
every environment

00:29.622 --> 00:31.872
with the keen eye
of the true detective.

00:32.957 --> 00:34.425
Watson, thoughts?

00:34.427 --> 00:38.178
Um, um...

00:38.180 --> 00:42.999
Looks like both men have been
shot in the chest one time.

00:43.001 --> 00:46.470
Judging from the scuff marks
on the concrete,

00:46.472 --> 00:48.806
looks like they chased
the suspect up here,

00:48.808 --> 00:52.059
who then fired twice
and then ran.

00:53.778 --> 00:56.563
It's tough to say where he went.

00:56.565 --> 00:59.066
The reason it's difficult
to say where he ran

00:59.068 --> 01:01.151
is that no one ran
anywhere at all.

01:02.120 --> 01:04.321
Here we have
two deceased gentlemen,

01:04.322 --> 01:06.657
both of them wearing
the uniform of ZBZ.

01:06.659 --> 01:08.242
Or so it would appear.

01:08.244 --> 01:11.027
This man's patches were
recently sewn on,

01:11.029 --> 01:12.880
and his clothes are
store-bought,

01:12.882 --> 01:15.165
not made by
a uniform company.

01:15.167 --> 01:17.534
So he was posing as a guard.

01:17.536 --> 01:19.703
Nothing is missing
from the museum,

01:19.705 --> 01:22.756
so we assume that he was looking
for access to the parking lot.

01:22.758 --> 01:24.391
It's easy to rifle
through the cars

01:24.393 --> 01:26.477
if you look like you work
for the security firm.

01:26.479 --> 01:27.978
Now, what was in
his pockets? Pockets?

01:27.980 --> 01:29.980
Pockets.

01:37.572 --> 01:40.190
Yeah, see, you thought
he was a victim,

01:40.192 --> 01:42.109
so you were looking
for identification.

01:42.111 --> 01:44.828
But here we have
one, two, three, four

01:44.830 --> 01:46.229
car registration cards.

01:46.231 --> 01:48.165
Each one has
the owner's address on it.

01:48.167 --> 01:49.733
See the game?

01:49.735 --> 01:52.903
Pick an expensive car,
then you call an associate,

01:52.905 --> 01:55.238
who burgles the home
of its owner while they're out.

01:55.240 --> 01:57.407
This man is
a real security guard.

01:57.409 --> 02:00.377
He saw this fellow
lurking around, followed him.

02:00.379 --> 02:02.012
Bad man shoots good man.

02:02.014 --> 02:03.597
Good man, while still alive,

02:03.599 --> 02:06.633
wrests control of gun
from bad man, fires one shot.

02:06.635 --> 02:08.301
Here we are.

02:08.304 --> 02:09.803
One more thing.

02:09.805 --> 02:11.271
His cell phone.

02:11.273 --> 02:13.724
You're gonna check
the last number he dialed;

02:13.726 --> 02:15.025
that's his partner.

02:15.027 --> 02:17.194
He's probably robbing
a place right now.

02:19.614 --> 02:21.615
Would you like to talk
to the burglar?

02:21.617 --> 02:25.285
According to this,
his name is Loco Maurice.

02:25.287 --> 02:28.989
You mustn't allow your failure
to discourage you.

02:28.991 --> 02:31.992
Didn't fail.
Not discouraged.

02:31.994 --> 02:34.545
You didn't solve the case,
but you did notice

02:34.547 --> 02:36.279
the incongruity
of the scuff marks.

02:36.281 --> 02:37.664
The next step is learning

02:37.666 --> 02:39.883
to extrapolate your way
to the truth.

02:39.885 --> 02:41.668
Detection is not just
a skill, Watson.

02:41.670 --> 02:43.253
It's a point of view.

02:43.255 --> 02:44.922
You must train yourself
to be alert

02:44.924 --> 02:46.423
to the bizarre,
the unusual,

02:46.425 --> 02:50.177
that which has no place
in any given picture.

02:50.179 --> 02:51.512
Like that stretch limo

02:51.514 --> 02:53.514
with the driver staring
straight at us?

02:53.516 --> 02:54.565
Sherlock Holmes?

02:54.567 --> 02:56.299
My name's Crabtree.

02:56.301 --> 02:58.852
We got your name from
a Mr. Musgrave in London.

02:58.854 --> 03:01.271
Local police told us
we'd find you here.

03:01.273 --> 03:03.323
Oh. You say "we."

03:03.325 --> 03:05.141
All I see is a you.

03:05.143 --> 03:07.194
I'm a driver and attaché

03:07.196 --> 03:09.079
for Mr. Gerald Lydon
of Lydon Industries.

03:09.081 --> 03:10.664
You know the company?

03:10.666 --> 03:12.032
You make everything
from Scotch Tape

03:12.034 --> 03:13.667
to diamond-tipped drill bits.

03:13.669 --> 03:16.286
Well, we have all the tape
and drill bits that we need.

03:16.288 --> 03:17.621
Thank you very much.

03:17.623 --> 03:19.706
Mr. Lydon has a proposal
for you.

03:23.261 --> 03:26.129
I sit before you a lucid man.

03:26.131 --> 03:28.098
Vital, I might say.

03:28.100 --> 03:30.851
I hold 18 patents

03:30.853 --> 03:33.670
and I can do 11 pull-ups
at age 58.

03:33.672 --> 03:36.557
And I own exactly
16 forks.

03:36.559 --> 03:38.174
I'm not entirely sure

03:38.176 --> 03:40.027
what we're supposed
to be comparing.

03:40.029 --> 03:44.314
Well, the point, Mr. Holmes,
is that in my good moments,

03:44.316 --> 03:46.400
I'm every bit
the man I was.

03:46.402 --> 03:48.652
But there are fewer
and fewer of those

03:48.654 --> 03:50.037
because I have dementia.

03:50.039 --> 03:51.822
And it's getting worse,

03:51.824 --> 03:55.025
which is why Ms. Tompkins
is following me around.

03:55.027 --> 03:56.877
You have my
condolences.

03:56.879 --> 03:59.079
I don't want your condolences.

03:59.081 --> 04:01.164
I want your help.

04:01.166 --> 04:03.033
Have you ever heard

04:03.035 --> 04:05.869
of hereditary cerebral
amyloid angiopathy?

04:05.871 --> 04:07.804
Hereditary CAA.

04:07.806 --> 04:09.840
It's a genetic disorder.

04:09.842 --> 04:12.342
Less than 20,000
cases recorded.

04:12.344 --> 04:13.894
Dementia is one

04:13.896 --> 04:15.312
of the early symptoms.

04:15.314 --> 04:16.930
And death is the final symptom.

04:16.932 --> 04:20.317
And when it comes to me,
it will complete my murder,

04:20.319 --> 04:24.054
because somebody did this to me,
and I need you to find out who.

04:24.056 --> 04:27.357
So, it's a hereditary disorder.

04:27.359 --> 04:29.526
You have to be born with it.

04:29.528 --> 04:32.613
And there's no history
of it in my family.

04:32.615 --> 04:35.282
They can do a lot of things
in labs now, you know.

04:35.284 --> 04:37.417
And I've consulted with
some of the top geneticists,

04:37.419 --> 04:39.119
and they tell me
that it's possible

04:39.121 --> 04:41.088
that somebody gave me
this disease,

04:41.090 --> 04:42.756
because they want me
out of power!

04:42.758 --> 04:45.125
With all due respect,

04:45.127 --> 04:47.577
maybe these
geneticists are right.

04:47.579 --> 04:50.797
"Possible" does
not mean "likely".

04:50.799 --> 04:53.750
It just means it's
not impossible.

04:53.752 --> 04:56.753
That's what my family says,
that's what the police say,

04:56.755 --> 04:59.556
that I'm paranoid,
that I'm delusional.

04:59.558 --> 05:02.258
I hate to say this, but those
are also symptoms of CAA.

05:02.260 --> 05:05.612
Look, they tell me
that you're the best.

05:05.614 --> 05:08.949
Mr. Holmes, what will it cost
to buy you over to my side?

05:08.951 --> 05:13.153
I only take cases when I believe
I'm acting in good faith.

05:13.155 --> 05:16.623
Now, since I think that
naturally occurring dementia

05:16.625 --> 05:19.626
is by far and away
the most likely explanation

05:19.628 --> 05:23.497
for your plight,
I would not be doing that.

05:23.499 --> 05:26.783
Would you pull over,
please, Crabtree?

05:26.785 --> 05:28.284
I really am
truly sorry.

05:28.286 --> 05:30.887
And I wish you
the best of luck.

